Web.ec page templates and tags

Web.ec operates using special tags that control the loading, operation and data-retrieval of Web.ec pages. When you purchase Web.ec, TopForm provides template pages embedded with these tags. You can completely customize the graphical "look and feel" and rename of the template pages according to your requirements. However, the Web.ec page tags must be used on these pages according to TopForm specifications.

Template Page Tag Types

The following table lists and describes the types of page tags used on the Web.ec template pages. Below that is the TopForm Web.ec Web Template Documentation.

Template Page Tag Type

Purpose / Use

Lead-In Parameters

These parameters are passed via a CGI call from the ecclient.pl process to the ecserver.pl process in the #.ec file.  Lead-In Parameters define the parameters required to link to the requested page such as the Web.ec basic program and template used to generate the page. For example, Lead-In Parameters basic=EC3P0 and template=prdcat.htm would generate the Buyer's product catalog using the prdcat.htm page as the template. See Web.ec system components and .

Page Control Tags

These tags are used to identify sections of the page for replication, heading identification, etc. Examples of Page Control tags include the tags for table layout,  drop-down lists, buttons, and links.

Data Tags

These tags are used to define the parameters for the data retrieved from the TopForm Server.

Product Catalog:  Page Control Tags

The following tags are used to identify sections of the page for replication, heading identification, etc.. Please note that the <! Leading HTML format causes this to be interpreted as a comment and will be ignored in your design or preview of the page.

 

Control Tag

HTML Requirement

<?tf?category_list?>

Category Drop Down List

This tag needs to be placed within a form that contains the a drop down list. This tag needs to follow the <select> tag in the HTML source.

 

<select><?tf?category_list?>

 

 

Drop Down Box Naming Convention

The drop down box must be named “category” so that it will be the value returned to TopForm WebEC will be the category selected. The parameters passed in by the CGI Post should be the remaining lead-in parameters.

<?tf?catalog_list?>

Catalog Drop Down List

This tag needs to be placed within a form that contains the a drop down list. This tag needs to follow the <select> tag in the HTML source.

 

<select><?tf?catalog_list?>

 

 

Drop Down Box Naming Convention

The drop down box must be named “catalog” so that it will be the value returned to TopForm WebEC will be the category selected. The parameters passed in by the CGI Post should be the remaining lead-in parameters.

 

! Must be Jump Drop Down List !

Use of the catalog drop-down list must post with a change in the selection in order to have web.ec update the category drop-down list accordingly.

<!?tf?entrystart?>

<!?tf?entryend>?

These tags need to surround the rows of your HTML table that will be repeated for the product catalog item codes.

<!?tf?buttonnext?>

<!?tf?buttonnextend?>

This should surround the next button element on your page

<!?tf?buttonprev?>

<!?tf?buttonprevend?>

This should surround the previous button element on your page

Tags for Support of “Single” order button and “Variable” print ordering

<!?tf?allorderstart?>

<!?tf?allorderend?>

These tags would be used if supporting separate sections for variable and non-variable print proofing items.

Only will display non-variable print items (ie. Items with a blank 3rd party id field on E/C-S3)

These tags need to surround the rows of you HTML table row that will be repeated for all items that are not utilizing the 3rd party id field for interfacing with on-line variable print tools.

<!?tf?3porderstart?>

<!?tf?3porderend?>

These tags would be used if supporting separate sections for variable and non-variable print proofing items.

Only will display variable print items (ie. Items that have an entry in the 3rd party field on E/C-S3)

These tags need to surround the rows of you HTML table row that will be repeated for all items that are utilizing the 3rd party id field for interfacing with on-line variable print tools.

<!?tf?buttonallstart?>

<!?tf?buttonallend?>

This should surround the button used to submit the form containing the product catalog item lines.

Quantity Break Pricing (ONLY AVAILABLE IF STOCK ITEM)

<!?tf?qtybreakstart?>

<!?tf?qtybreakend?>

These tags need to surround the HTML section where quantity break pricing needs to be displayed. These tags must be inside the line section tags (entrystart/end, 3porderstart/end, allorderstart/end).

 

Note:  This section will not be displayed if the corresponding item key within TopForm has a customer code value (ie. It must only be a stock item).

“Details” Sections for Product Types: 

  • Warehouse Release
  • Exact Repeat
  • Stock Inventory

<!?tf?infowrstart?>

<!?tf?infowrend?>

These tags need to surround the HTML section that contains the “Details” hyperlink for a warehouse release type product. If the item is either a stock product or flagged to “Create a PO” then this section will not be returned.

 

These tags must be inside the line section tags (entrystart/end, 3porderstart/end, allorderstart/end).

 

 

Note: An icon or other text (not containing data tags to be processed) may be placed within these data tags in order to identify the product type to on-line buyers.

 

Avail:  8/27/02

<!?tf?infopostart?>

<!?tf?infopoend?>

These tags need to surround the HTML section that contains the “Details” hyperlink for an exact repeat type product. If the item is either a stock product or flagged to NOT “Create a PO” then this section will not be returned

 

These tags must be inside the line section tags (entrystart/end, 3porderstart/end, allorderstart/end).

 

Note: An icon or other text (not containing data tags to be processed) may be placed within these data tags in order to identify the product type to on-line buyers.

 

Avail:  8/27/02

<!?tf?infostockstart?>

<!?tf?infostockend?>

These tags need to surround the HTML section that contains the “Details” hyperlink for a stock product type product. This is indicated by a product that has no associated customer in the product identification. If the item is not a stock product then this section will not be returned

 

These tags must be inside the line section tags (entrystart/end, 3porderstart/end, allorderstart/end).

 

Note: An icon or other text (not containing data tags to be processed) may be placed within these data tags in order to identify the product type to on-line buyers.\

 

Quantity break note: The qtybreakstart/end cannot be included within these tags

 

Avail:  8/27/02

Special Processing Notes for Product Catalog Detail

Usage Reporting

For the reporting of usage figures, it makes a big difference if the page is to be reporting information for a single customer location or all locations. The reporting of customer ship-to location information is based on the customer location code on the buyer's record.

 

In order to allow the same page to be used for location based buyers and non-location based buyer (blank customer location), if the customer location is not specified the information will be replaced with the information for all locations.

 

Usage Query Tags

In the event that you want to allow your client to specify the usage year to be seen (instead of defaulting to the current year based on their F/M parameters), you could have a lead-in form page that queries the buyer for any of the following information before completing the link to the product catalog detail page. The name of the text entry boxes in your forms would correspond to the data tags given below. without the ?tf? prefix and ? suffix. The other standard lead-in parameters would need to be parameters in your form properties.

 

usage_year

4

YYYY format (for usage queries)

usage_bal_type

1

U - usage   C - budgets

Available: January 10, 2002

Data Tag

Description

Data Tag Format

The data tags use the following format

 

?tf?<datatag>?[x]

 

where x is the order history occurance

1 = most recent order

2 = prior order

3 = prior order

etc.

 

Example:

To report information on the last 3 orders:

 

?tf?fmz_cust_po?[1]  ?tf?fmz_activity_dt?[1]  ?tf?fmz_order_qty?[1]

?tf?fmz_cust_po?[2]  ?tf?fmz_activity_dt?[2]  ?tf?fmz_order_qty?[2]

?tf?fmz_cust_po?[3]  ?tf?fmz_activity_dt?[3]  ?tf?fmz_order_qty?[3]

Simple Order Totaling

(Available: January 1, 2003)

These tags offer the ability to have simple line extensions and overall shopping cart totals based on the order quantity and the unit price.

WARNING:  These calculations are done using information from the custom item master price and fms price fields. On creation of an order in TopForm via the order entry gateway, different pricing may result on the order due to pricing set on the inventory lot record. As such, these prices are not guaranteed as the price to be created on the order. In order to get guaranteed pricing as well as sales tax and delivery charges, the credit card processing module should be used.

<!?tf?wslineend?>

Direct Order Access Form

TopForm WebEC supports user definable order status sorts. The system allows for up to three (3) sorts based order header information and three (3) sorts based on ship-to location information. A sort may contain multiple sort elements not exceeding a total length of 44 characters. In supporting the ability to go directly to an order, TopForm WebEC allows for the buyer to enter in the high order sort element. For example, if orders are sorted by customer P/O and then order date, the client can go directly to the high-order element, the customer P/O field. The following name needs to be used for the form field value, with a length equal to the data being sorted.

 

The form CGI parameters being the standard parameters given above. The text entry box containing the requested client P/O number should be named “position_cust_po”.

position_cust_po

15

This field may be used for searching on the customer P/O number

order_position_key

Length equal to element being sorted

Item Keyword Search:  Page Control Tags

Control Tag

HTML Requirement

<?tf?category_search_list>?

Category Drop Down List (Searching)

This will generate a drop down list of Product Catalog Categories. This would be used if you want to allow the user to specify which category will be searched. “ALL Categories will automatically be added as an option on the list.

 

Note:  Only the categories available to the buyer will be populated into the drop down list.

 

Category Drop Down List

This tag needs to be placed after a form that contains the a drop down list. This tag needs to follow the <select> tag in the HTML source.

 

<source><?tf?category_search_list?>

 

Note:  “ALL categories option missing – Check to see if you have a <!?tf?… instead of <?tf?…

Drop Down Box Naming Convention

The drop down box must be named “category” so that it will be the value returned to TopForm WebEC will be the category selected. The parameters passed in by the CGI Post should be the remaining lead-in parameters.

<?tf?catalog_search_list?>

Catalog Drop Down List

This tag needs to be placed within a form that contains the a drop down list. This tag needs to follow the <select> tag in the HTML source.

 

<source><?tf?catalog_list?>

 

 

Drop Down Box Naming Convention

The drop down box must be named “catalog” so that it will be the value returned to TopForm WebEC will be the category selected. The parameters passed in by the CGI Post should be the remaining lead-in parameters.

 

Search Element Data Tags

These are the elements on the form/product that can be searched. Any combination of these elements can be added as needed. If multiple elements are specified by a buyer, then all of the search elements will be applied in an “and” logical evaluation.

 

The following applies to the searching:

·        the field lengths identifies the maximum field width that can be searched

·        the search entries are not case sensitive (the buyer’s entry and your TopForm database element value are both converted to uppercase before any comparisons are made)

·        Combination of the fields create a logical “and” evaluation situation.

·        THE FOLLOWING FIELDS MUST BE SUBMITTED WITHIN A FORM. See the Item Search Results page lead-in parameters for the lead-in parameters.

Start Data Tags

The inventory report start page can either allow the user to specify a category, list of categories or ALL categories. In addition to this you can also allow the user to use either a key word search to determine the items to report or use the product catalog to sequence the information.

Key Word Search Element Data Tags

These are the elements on the form/product that can be searched. Any combination of these elements can be added as needed. If multiple elements are specified by a buyer, then all of the search elements will be applied in an “and” logical evaluation.

 

The following applies to the searching:

·        the field lengths identifies the maximum field width that can be searched

·        the search entries are not case sensitive (the buyer’s entry and your TopForm database element value are both converted to uppercase before any comparisons are made)

·        Combination of the fields create a logical “and” evaluation situation.

·        THE FOLLOWING FIELDS MUST BE SUBMITTED WITHIN A FORM. See the Item Search Results page lead-in parameters for the lead-in parameters.

Lot Inventory Record Reporting

 

The reporting of lot inventory record information is currently available in the following areas:

 

  • Product catalog detail
    • Based on the warehouses currently listed as the default supplying warehouse(s) for the buyer
  • Order worksheet pages (shopping cart prior to buy)
    • Reporting lot records that would be selected if order were purchased
    • Note: The reported lot records is an only an estimate. Since the records are not yet committed to a completed order, any order for the product placed prior to the existing order in-process would be allocated the stock first. Reporting of this information to your web clients should only be done with situation clearly understood.

 

  • Order confirmation page
    • Reporting lot records committed to the generated order

 

Page Control Tags

In order for the information to be reported, a table row or row(s) needs to designed onto your web page template and surrounded with the following page control tags.

HTML Requirement

<!?tf?lotlineend?>

The starting and ending tag should surround the row(s) of your HTML table that will be repeated for every order line.

 

Use on Order Entry Page(s)

These page control tags must appear within the order entry page controls tags of:

?tf?wslinestart?

?tf?wslineend?

or the information will not be reported correctly.

<select size="1" name="requested_location">?tf?shipto_ddlist?</select

Description

Will generate a drop down list of all non-excluded customer ship-to records.

?tf?ship_to_ddlist_all?

Will generate a drop down list of all non-excluded customer ship-to records including an initial selection for ALL locations.

 

Note:  If the buyer is tied to a specific ship-to location then the “ALL Ship-to Locations” will not be an available option.

Credit Card Processing – Special Notes

Credit Card Capture ONLY (No On-Line Billing)

This is a situation where webec is to be used to capture the credit card information related to the purchase but to not initiate on-line billing and the subsequent full order totaling from the invoice including sales tax and freight charges.

 

System Settings

The following must be true:

 

  • Credit Card Module Installed
  • A/R System Parameter set to “Y” to activate credit card processing
  • E/C System Parameter – Screen IV “Credit Card Capture Only – no ‘ccaction on page” set to “Y”

 

Page Requirements

Prior to purchasing the order, the web site must prompt the buyer as to whether the purchase is a credit card order or terms order (on purchase order). This question must submit the following parameter

 

Purchase Type Question

‘

Parameter

Value

cc_required

Y – credit card purchase

N – on terms (P/O)

 

Redirect to Credit Card Entry Pages

If the purchase is to contain the capture of credit card information then the buyer must be redirected to pages that contain entry/display options for the credit card information. If the purchase were on terms, then the check out process would proceed without this information.

 

The redirect is handled with the following lead-in parameters

 

Lead-in Parameter

Value

basic

EC3WS1

session_id

?tf?session_id?

template

<template to be used for on-terms purchase>

cctemplate

<template to redirect to that contains credit card display/entry>

 

Note:  Webec will redirect to this page in place of the template value if the cc_required value has previously been submitted with a “Y” value.

 

Credit Card Information & Display

See information regarding credit card processing under “Order Entry EC3WS1”

TopForm WebEC is fully functional on the support of both client and product images. With the flexibility of configuration that TopForm WebEC offers, you have several parameter controls that allow for the identification of image naming conventions and location.

 

Required Decisions to be Made

Image Storage Location

The first thing you will need to decide is the location of your images. They may reside on your web server or your TopForm UNIX server. For recommendations, please contact your TopForm representative. Your main consideration in this area should be both storage capacity of the server and ensuring adequate backup procedures

 

Single Image Directory

To configure for a single image directory, simply enter in the image directory path in your TopForm WebEC system parameters. No entry should be made in any Customer Parameters. If you will be supporting form images, you will need to include the customer code as part of the form image in order to avoid duplication of image names if only the form code were to be used.

 

Separate Image Directories by Client

If you would like to maintain separate image directories by client you will need to enter in the full image path in on the Customer Parameters screen for each client you are supporting on the web. In this situation you may decide to use the form code as the image name since the separate directories by client will ensure no duplication of names even if the same form code is being used for multiple web clients.

 

Form Images

The decision to place form images on your WebEC pages is a very popular feature that many distributors are looking to offer their web based clients. With TopForm WebEC you may decide to support form images selectively by buyer. This may be accomplished using the “Web Code” setting on the buyer record which can be set to use HTML templates that have the data tags for the form images.

 

The administration of you WebEC site will increase directly with the increase in the number of web based clients for whom you will be supporting images. Since there is no way in a web page environment to verify if an image is on file. If you decide to support images, you will need to have images for all forms/products placed on the web in order to avoid the populated web pages returning the dreaded “X” image box.

 

You may either store all of your web based images in a single directory or maintain separate directories for each client.

Company Logos

TopForm WebEC can dynamically display your company logo. The logo is needs to be stored in each customer image directory. The name of the logo file is pulled from the customer’s EC parameters. If the customer EC parameter for company logo is blank then the logo file name is pulled from the EC system parameters. The following data tags are globally available on all web template pages.

 

company_logo

 

This tag will return the complete HTML necessary for the display of the logo

company_logo_image_source

 

This tag should be used in the HTML code following the “img src=”. This option allows for you to better control sizing and attributes

 

Customer Images

TopForm WebEC currently supports the automatic placement of a client logo on all WebEC pages. This is accomplished by placing the data tag identified below at the location that you desire the logo to be displayed.

 

cust_logo

The customer’s logo

 

 

Client Image File Name Specification

You will need to enter in the image file name on the Customer Parameters screen for each of your web based clients. This file name will be appended on to the image path (either from the customer parameter record if separate image directories are desired or from the WebEC system parameters).

Form Images

TopForm WebEC currently support five (5) images per form that you place on the web. These images may be used either for simple image placement or as an image source in a hyperlink. Form images are currently available for display on the following pages.

 

  • Product Catalog
  • Product Catalog Detail
  • Item Search Results Page

 

Following are the data tags that may be used to identify the form image to be used on these pages.

 

Image_form1

These are the data tags to be used for simple image display

Image_form2

Image_form3

Image_form4

Image_form5

Image_form1_link

These are the data tags to be used for display of an image as an image source in a hyperlink

Image_form2_link

Image_form3_link

Image_form4_link

Image_form5_link

 

Form Image Name Specification

The form image file names can be set up on the WebEC form parameters screen. On this screen you will see five (5) fields for specification of the form image name. Each form image field (1, 2, 3, etc.) corresponds to the data tags described above. These file names will be appended on to the image path (either from the customer parameter record if separate image directories are desired or from the WebEC system parameters).

User Definable Form Image Labels

As a part of your TopForm WebEC system, you can define the purpose of form images being used on your web commerce pages. These purposes might include a thumbnail, a low resolution graphic, a high resolution graphic, an icon, etc.. By defining labels for the five (5) form image fields, you won’t have to remember which image is for what purpose.

 

To define the labels, modify your WebEC system parameters and enter in the labels.

 

Maintenance of Form Images

When we are speaking of multiple images supported for a single form for different purposes, each of the image files will contain the following format:

 

            <image file name> + <image suffix>

 

The image file name is either going to be the customer code plus form code or simply the form code. The image suffix will contain an identifier for the file purpose (i.e. lr for low resolution) as well as the full extension based on the type of graphical file (.gif, .jpg).

Automated Using the Web Catalog Load Utility

Your TopForm WebEC system comes with a catalog loading utility. This utility allows for the loading of forms into the web catalog for a client based on a number of loading criteria. Included in this loading utility is the identification if form image names are to be created as part of the process.

 

Form Image Format field

In this field you have the following options for selecting the format of the form image file names.

 

C

Customer Code (raw format) + Form Code

 

This means that the customer code will contain the two character division number followed by an eight character customer code. There will be no formatting applied to the customer code. If you customer number was  01-00500 then the resulting customer number in a raw format would be 0100500000.

D

Customer Code (formatted) + Form Code

 

The customer code in this option would be the same as it appears in your TopForm system. If you are divisionalized, it will also contain the hyphen.

F

The image file will be the form code

N

No loading of the form image names

 

Image File Extensions

If you choose one of the automated image formats, you will be prompted to enter the image file suffix for each of the five (5) image file types. Following are some suggestions using a .jpg format:

 

Suggested Suffix

File Purpose

lr.jpg

low resolution graphic

tn.jgp

thumbnail

hr.jpg

high resolution graphic

icon.jpg

icon

 

Manual Form Image File Maintenance

To manually set or change form image file names, simply modify the WebEC form parameters.

 

Tip:  For those forms that you may not have yet acquired an image you should create an image or icon that identifies that the form is currently not available or is under revision. Place the name of this “NOF” image in the form parameters to avoid getting the “X” no image available box.
